This paper deals with the problem of dynamically allocating networking resources in 5G networks, which is a key issue in the field of network infrastructure (NI). The authors model the slicing problem as a congestion game, which is a topic in game theory (GT). They also propose distributed algorithms that converge to a unique Nash equilibrium, which involves information theory (IT) and control systems (SY). Finally, they evaluate their algorithms through simulations and an experimental testbed, which involves distributed computing (DC).
